I was very saddened to hear of the passing of Dr. James Dobson. Dr. Dobson was certainly one of the most influential leaders in America in the last century. Dr. Dobson had a major impact on Ann and me and our children. We first became aware of Dr. Dobson in the mid-1980s at our church through a video series of his lessons on marriage and child rearing. 

Later, in 1989, I was one of a small group of people chosen to participate in a special conference at the Focus on Family headquarters that led to the founding of the Alabama Family Alliance, that later became the Alabama Policy Institute, as part of a national network of family policy councils. In that regard, Dr. Dobson has had a huge impact in Alabama.

I last talked with him in May and had a chance to thank him for all he has meant to countless millions of people and to my family and me. He was, without question, one of the most influential American leaders in the last 50 years whose voice impacted the lives of millions of families promoting a culture based on the biblical values needed to sustain our nation at a time when those values have been under relentless attack. His more than 70 books and weekday radio broadcast covered the full spectrum of marriage and family from couples just starting out to finishing well in our later years. Dr. Dobson lived what he wrote and spoke about; he finished well. 

Ann and I are praying for his wife Shirley, their children, their grandchildren, and that God will give them comfort and that they will feel the gratitude of all who were so blessed by Dr. Dobson’s ministry.

🚨The SAVE Act just passed the House.

We are one step closer to protecting our elections and enforcing the common-sense idea that only American citizens should vote in American elections. 

Thank you to @RepChipRoy for his leadership on this issue. Proud to be an original co-sponsor on the SAVE Act.

In short, the SAVE Act is necessary to ensure only American citizens are voting in American elections. 

This is not voter suppression. This is about protecting free and fair elections.
U.S. Service members deployed abroad will still be able to vote because the SAVE Act does not amend the Uniformed Overseas Citizens Absentee Voting Act.

Yes, it is already illegal for non-citizens to vote in federal elections. So why is the SAVE Act necessary? 

The National Voter Registration Act (NVRA) prevents the law from being enforced.

The SAVE Act will require states to verify the citizenship status of individuals when registering to vote while also equipping states to remove non-citizens from their voter rolls and penalize officials that do not enforce the law.

There has been proof of non-citizens voting in American elections. 

In Alabama alone, our Secretary of State attempted to remove 3,251 non-citizens from our voter roles in 2024 before Biden’s liberal DOJ intervened. 

The Biden border crisis allowed millions of illegal aliens to enter our country. We must ensure only American citizens are voting in American elections.

The SAVE Act will NOT prohibit individuals from voting that have changed their name. 

As long as they have updated their documentation and their new name is on a document proving citizenship (like a REAL ID, passport, etc), they can register to vote without issues. 

If their documentation has not yet been updated, the SAVE Act explicitly directs states to create a process for them to register to vote regardless of the discrepancies as long as they have documentation to prove citizenship.

Preventing non-citizens from voting in American elections should not be controversial. 

Today, @HouseGOP will pass the SAVE Act and protect the integrity of our elections!

Today marks the 83rd anniversary of the attack on Pearl Harbor.

Dozens of Alabamians were killed on this tragic day, including 32 on the USS Arizona and Julius Ellsberry, who was believed to be the first Black Alabamian to die in World War II.

Today, we honor the memory of all these brave Alabamians, but I would like to specifically focus on Chief Carpenter John Arnold Austin from Warrior, Alabama.

On the morning of December 7th, John was on board the USS Oklahoma, which was the first ship to be attacked by the Japanese on Battleship Row. John and many of his shipmates found themselves trapped, but he found an escape route and is credited with saving 15 sailors that day. Unfortunately, he perished in the process.

Chief Carpenter Austin was awarded the Navy Cross posthumously. His citation reads, "He gallantly gave his life in the service of his country." The USS Austin, a destroyer escort, was later named in his honor.

As we honor those lost, let us remember and reflect on their sacrifices and the high cost required to preserve freedom.
